issue_body:
It's possible to filter guild messages from specific users using the following endpoints.
```
/guilds/{}/messages/search?author_id={}&include_nsfw=true&count=25&offset={}
/channels/{}/messages/search?author_id={}&include_nsfw=true&count=25&offset={}
```

This returns JSON structured like so. Messages are ordered most recent descending.
```javascript
{
    "messages": [
        [
            {
                // Message context. 
            },
            {
                // Message context. 
            },
            {
                // A message sent by the user we are filtering. This is always message[2].
            },
            {
                // Message context. 
            },
            {
                // Message context.
            }
        ],
        ...
    ]
}
```

I will be happy to submit a PR for this if the functionality is approved.

I am applying widget on a table which has first row hidden and n rows visible.
On applying the widget, the row for search box gets extended to an extra column. Please find the widget configuration below. Using version: '2.26.0'

`var tableEmptyDependencyStyleOption = $.extend(true, {}, globals.tableSorterOptions, {
			// sort on the first column in ascending order, Hidden columns are considered for numbering
			sortList: [[0, 0]],
			widgets: ['zebra'],//, 'resizable'
			widgetOptions: {
				filter_cellFilter: ['disabled', '', '', '', '', 'disabled'],
				filter_columnFilters: true,
				filter_cssFilter: "form-control",
			},`

I was having some issues outputting a CSV with multiple header rows, some of which included colspan attributes. I resolved the issue by modifying my local widget-output file, but I wanted to share the issues I was having here. 

The issue was that the colspan headers were being repeated an appropriate amount of times, except for the first cell, which was repeating twice instead of the specified four times. My issue was in the process colspans section of the code. 

When looping through to colspanLen, it starts from an index of one 
for (col = 1; col <= colspanLen; col++)

Then when it was supposed to increase the cellIndex count based on the number of filled cells in this line
while (typeof tmpRow[rowIndex][cellIndex] !== 'undefined') { cellIndex++; }
it would start from index of zero. Since the colspan iteration starts from 1, the element in the 0 position of the temporary row was always undefined, and would break the loop. 

The solution that has worked for me is to change the colspan iteration to be zero indexed. 
for (col = 0; col < colspanLen; col++)

